def analyze_image(img):
    f, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(16, 4), sharex=True)
    # type of image and its shape
    print(type(img), img.shape)
    # let's check 
    img_matrix = Image.open("rgb_image.png")
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.imshow(img_matrix)
    colors = ["Red", "Green", "Blue"]
    for i, color in enumerate(colors):
        color_values = img[:,:, i]
        print(f"\n{color} color values: {color_values} \n Mean value: {color_values.mean()} \n")
        sns.distplot(img[:, :, i], color=color, ax=axes[i]);
    print(" ______________ \n Color histogram: \n")

Opencv hist implementation¶

With nice output functionality¶

In [86]:
def hist_image(img_path: str):
    # convert to rgb
    img = cv2.imread(img_path)[:, :, ::-1]
    # tuple of colors 
    colors = ('r','g','b')
    # create figure
    plt.figure()
    # Create nice subplots
    f, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2,figsize=(15,5))
    g, (ax21, ax22, ax23) = plt.subplots(1,3, figsize=(15,3))
    # iterate through list of images and make hists out of it
    for i,color in enumerate(colors):
        histr = cv2.calcHist([img],[i],None,[256],[0,256])
        if color == 'r':
            ax21.plot(histr, color = color)
        if color == 'g':
            ax22.plot(histr, color = color)
        if color == 'b':
            ax23.plot(histr, color = color)
        ax1.plot(histr,color = color)

    ax2.imshow(img)
    plt.show()
